"Lemoine N., Schaefer H.-C., Böhning-Gaese K.","Species richness of migratory birds is influenced by global climate change",2007,"Global Ecology and Biogeography","16","1",,"55","64",,,10.1111/j.1466-8238.2006.00252.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33845630329&partnerID=40&md5=d318bde868303ae16575b9da5aa3550f","Institut für Zoologie, Abt. Ökologie, Johannes Gutenberg-Universität Mainz, Becherweg 13, 55099 Mainz, Germany; Virtual Institute Macroecology, Theodor-Lieser-Str. 4, 06120 Halle, Germany","Lemoine, N., Institut für Zoologie, Abt. Ökologie, Johannes Gutenberg-Universität Mainz, Becherweg 13, 55099 Mainz, Germany; Schaefer, H.-C., Institut für Zoologie, Abt. Ökologie, Johannes Gutenberg-Universität Mainz, Becherweg 13, 55099 Mainz, Germany, Virtual Institute Macroecology, Theodor-Lieser-Str. 4, 06120 Halle, Germany; Böhning-Gaese, K., Institut für Zoologie, Abt. Ökologie, Johannes Gutenberg-Universität Mainz, Becherweg 13, 55099 Mainz, Germany","Aim: Global climate change is increasingly influencing ecosystems. Long-term effects on the species richness and composition of ecological communities have been predicted using modelling approaches but, so far, hardly demonstrated in the field. Here, we test whether changes in the composition of bird communities have been influenced by recent climate change. Location: Europe. Methods: We focus on the proportion of migratory and resident bird species because these groups are expected to respond differently to climatic change. We used the spatial relationship between climatic factors and bird communities in Europe to predict changes in 21 European bird communities under recent climate change. Results: Observed changes corresponded significantly to predicted changes and could not be explained by the effects of spatial autocorrelation. Alternative factors such as changes in land use were tested in a first approximation as well but no effects were found. Main conclusions: This study demonstrates that global climate change has already influenced the species richness and composition of European bird communities. © 2006 The Authors Journal compilation © 2006 Blackwell Publishing Ltd.","Bird community composition; Europe; Future predictions; GCM; Long-distance migrants; Model validation","bird; ecological impact; ecological modeling; environmental factor; global change; migratory species; species richness; Eurasia; Europe; Aves",,,,,,"Andrew, N.R., Hughes, L., Species diversity and structure of phytophagous beetle assemblages along a latitudinal gradient: Predicting the potential impacts of climate change (2004) Ecological Entomology, 29, pp. 527-542; Bauer, H.-G., Heine, G., The development in the breeding birds of Lake Constance: A comparison of grid mapping in 1980/81 and 1990/92 (1992) Journal Für Ornithologie, 133, pp. 1-22; Bearhop, S., Fiedler, W., Furness, R.W., Votier, S.C., Waldron, S., Newton, J., Bowen, G.J., Farnsworth, K., Assortative mating as a mechanism for rapid evolution of a migratory divide (2005) Science, 21, pp. 502-504; Bergmann, G., Hyytiä, K., Kellomäki, E., Koistinnen, J., Lokki, J., (1983) Suomen Lintuatlas, , Luntutieto Oy, Helsinki; Berthold, P., Helbig, A.J., Mohr, G., Querner, U., Rapid microevolution of migratory behaviour in a wild bird species (1992) Nature, 360, pp. 668-670; (2004) Birds in the European Union: A Status Assessment, , BirdLife International BirdLife International, Wageningen; Böhning-Gaese, K., Lemoine, N., Importance of climate change for the ranges, communities and conservation of birds (2004) Birds and Climate Change, 35, pp. 211-236. , (ed. by A.P. Møller, W. Fiedler and P. Berthold), Advances in Ecological Research Elsevier Academic Press, London; Böhning-Gaese, K., Oberrath, R., Macroecology of habitat choice in long-distance migratory birds (2003) Oecologia, 137, pp. 296-303; Dunn, P., Breeding dates and reproductive performance (2004) Birds and Climate Change, 35, pp. 69-88. , (ed. by A.P. Møller, W. Fiedler a